, England":"Risby, Suffolk, England","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hollis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) holly or holly trees’, from Middle English <i>holi(e)</i>, <i>holin</i> (Old English <i>holegn</i>, <i>holen</i>). Compare   Hollen   and   Holley   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Holley","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>hol</i> ‘hollow’ + <i>eie</i>, <i>egh(e)</i> ‘eye’ (Old English <i>hol</i> + <i>ēage</i>), perhaps a nickname for someone with a missing eye.","topographic name for someone who lived by a ‘clearing in a hollow’, from Middle English <i>hol</i> ‘hollow’ + <i>lei(e)</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Hollins","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hollins (Staffordshire, Lancashire, Yorkshire), or else a topographic name from the plural of Middle English <i>holin</i> ‘holly’ (see   Hollis  )."]},{"name":"Holm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lars, Anders, Thor, Holger, Nels, Nils, Sven, Helmer, Lennart, Niels, Vibeke.","English, Scottish, German, and Scandinavian: topographic name for someone who lived on an island, in particular a piece of slightly raised land lying in a fen or partly surrounded by streams, from Middle English, Middle Low German <i>holm</i>, Old Norse <i>holmr</i>, or else a habitational name from a place called with this element. The Swedish name is often ornamental.","English: topographic name for someone who lived where holly grew, from Middle English <i>holm</i>, a divergent development of Old English <i>hole(g)n</i> ‘holly (tree)’; or, especially in southern England, a habitational name from any of the places such as East and West Holme (Dorset) or Holne (Devon). Compare   Hollis  ."]},{"name":"Hollen","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a holly tree, from Middle English <i>holin</i> ‘holly’ (Old English <i>holegn</i>). Compare   Hollis  .","Dutch: patronymic from   Holle   3."]},{"name":"Hollings","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Hollis  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Hollis was born in 1505, in Suffolk, England, his father, John Owles Hollis, was 40 and his mother, Rose Owlis, was 40. He married Elizabeth C Jones on 25 December 1519, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1542, in his hometown, at the age of 37, and was buried in Huntingfield, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1505–1542":"1505–1542","1485–1542":"1485–1542","1500–1542":"1500–1542","1520–1600":"1520–1600","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1465":"1465","1485":"1485","25 December 1519":"25. detsember 1519","1505":"1505","Risby, Suffolk, England":"Risby, Suffolk, England","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1505–1542":"1505–1542","1485–1542":"1485–1542","1500–1542":"1500–1542","1520–1600":"1520–1600","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1465":"1465","1485":"1485","25 December 1519":"25. joulukuuta 1519","1505":"1505","Risby, Suffolk, England":"Risby, Suffolk, England","Ravensthorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Ravensthorp